<div class="comments-body mattman206"> 
<p>I also use VisualSVN Server.  It&#39;s free and lets you set up a repository that&#39;s slightly different than what described here.</p>

<p>1) It uses Apache on Windows, and automatically creates an SSL (self-signed) certificate for you, so you can run it over HTTPS. (By doing it the way described in this article, you have no encryption -- everything is out in the open)<br />
2) It stores the password in hashes, not plaintext, by using the Apache htpasswd authentication mechanisms. <br />
3) It uses SVN authz files, which allow you have _granular_ control over a user&#39;s permissions for each directory inside each repository. And it provides the ability to control this in the GUI.</p>

<p>It has a great graphical interface, too. It&#39;s an MMC snapin, so it really makes it feel like it&#39;s a honest-to-goodness Windows service.</p>

<p>And did I mention that it&#39;s free? :)<br />
</p>
<span class="comments-post" style="margin-left:20px">mattman206 on April  6, 2008  6:51 AM</span> 
